  "topic_name": "Water",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Water (H₂O) is essential for life and covers about 71% of Earth's surface. The water cycle involves evaporation, condensation, and precipitation. Water has unique physical properties: boiling point 100°C, freezing point 0°C, maximum density at 4°C (anomalous expansion). Water is called the universal solvent because it dissolves many substances. Solutions can be saturated, unsaturated, or supersaturated. Water of crystallization is the fixed number of water molecules in a crystal. Hydrated salts contain water of crystallization; anhydrous salts do not. Hard water contains dissolved calcium and magnesium salts; it doesn't lather easily with soap. Hardness can be temporary (removed by boiling) or permanent (removed by chemical methods).",
